h1.a: Ravens' Skura set to practice after ACL recovery

div.p: Ravens center Matt Skura is expected to practice Sunday, completing a remarkable recovery after he tore the ACL, PCL and MCL in his left knee nine months ago.

Ravens center Matt Skura is expected to suit up for the team's first padded practice after passing his physical Sunday, the team announced. This completes an remarkable recovery for Skura, who tore the ACL, PCL and MCL in his left knee nine months ago. The Ravens had repeatedly said all offseason that Skura was ahead of schedule in his rehab and would return sometime in training camp.

h1.a: From 'Big Truss' to big brother, Mark Ingram remains the consummate leader

div.p: In his age-30 season, Ingram has taken rookie J.K. Dobbins under his sizable wings and spearheads a quadruple threat in the Ravens' backfield.

Ravens wide receiver Marquise "Hollywood" Brown feels reigning NFL MVP Lamar Jackson is even more motivated this season, especially after another quick exit from the postseason. "I feel like he's more hungry," Brown said. "He presses the issue about the Super Bowl. That's his No. 1 goal. He wants to win a Super Bowl. He wants to win more than one."

div.p: Ravens running bak Mark Ingram said his mindset hasn't changed even though he's now 30 and is facing increased competition from rookie second-round pick J.K. Dobbins. "The coaches will decide how to rotate us and play us all," Ingram said. "All I do is work my butt off. I compete my butt off no matter where I'm at and who's in my running back room. That's just the bottom line." Ingram tied a Ravens record with 15 total touchdowns last season and finished 14th in the NFL with 1,018 yards rushing.

Ravens starting center Matt Skura was placed on the Physically Unable to Perform list to begin training camp. Skura suffered a season-ending knee injury in November, but he's expected to return at some point in camp. "I'm optimistic about Matt, I really am," coach John Harbaugh said last week. "But we'll be careful."

div.p: Ravens rookie second-round pick J.K. Dobbins enters a crowded backfield with Mark Ingram and Gus Edwards. But Dobbins believes he can make an impact in his first season. "My goal ain't to be patient," Dobbins said. I'm not saying that I'm going to start or anything. I feel like if I work hard enough and show coaches I can play at this level, then I will be on the field. My goal is to help the team win a Super Bowl, not sit on the bench."
